commit.message: [doc] add more examples for the `comma` format

[feat] add the comma output format

These changes add the comma output format where results are represented
on one single line and separated by commas.

Also these changes:
- fix an issue with `newline` output when elements are not instance
  of string type.
- reindent properly the help format's part
- rename the unit test module related to the ouput module

How to test:
------------

Setup your env:

```sh
$ git add remote hberaud git@github.com:4383/niet
$ git fetch hberaud
$ git checkout -b comma hberaud/comma
```

Now run tests:

```sh
$ # Example of display
$ tox -e venv -- niet "oslo.deliverables.*.repos[0]"
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openstack/governance/master/reference/projects.yaml
-f comma
$ # Example of integration with beagle and the openstack governance data
$ tox -e venv -- beagle search -f link --repo \$\(niet
"oslo.deliverables.*.repos[0]"
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openstack/governance/master/reference/projects.yaml
-f comma\) 'venv'
```

[feat] retrieve input data from a raw web resource

Allow niet to fetch distant web resource to work on.

Drop support of py27

Python 2.7 is EOL since January 2020, these changes drop the related support

Manage virtual env through tox

These changes avoid to us to use pipenv or similar tools by
using tox's capabilities.

Also contribution guidelines are updated to match these changes.

Some requirements can be dropped since they are now managed by tox.

Drop python 3.4 support

Python 3.4 isn't maintained since March 2019 [1].

[1] https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0429/

fix use newline format on single value

When user try to extract a float we need to consider that this is a
single value to use the newline format like for string or int.
fix infilename retrieve if input come from stdin
[feat #11] Add in-place and output function to print output to a file
[doc] Improve contributing guide to explain how to run it locally explicitly

Introduce eval output

Allow user to eval the output with shell.
All the retrieved elements will become strings that can be transformed
in shell variables by using the linux eval command.
